        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&amp;REPLY_ID=39858&amp;TOPIC_ID=4992&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=Targetable+feign+%28idea%29&amp;M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="2" color="#545A7D">
        
         Sheeze "Wah Wah Wah"...  The fact is, there are lots of good ideas out there that have nothing to do with DOT stacking that could add depth to our class.  This is one of them.  If they apply it and you don't like it, fine.  Don't use it.  But the fact remains that none of these good ideas have to be mutually exclusive.  You want respect for a position of not applying an ability like this to our class - provide an argument better than "I don't like it."  From the response I've seen here and the fact that it got accepted to the developer boards in the first place, I'd suggest that many more people would be 'thrilled' for an addition like this.  You don't have to do backflips for every change, but don't begrudge those of us who feel we'd gain from something like this, unless you can present a good case for how it would be demonstrably uncharacteristic for our class.</P><P>The fact is "Feigning Death" IS characteristically natural for a necromancer.  And the ability to lend that capacity to another is similarly in line with an ideal of what the class might represent - much more so than a monk, shaman or shadowknight.</P><P>Again, if you don't like it, and they saw fit to add it... don't use it.  The rest of us will be laughing all the way to the bank as we find our role and desirability on raids increased that much more.</P><P>I think too many people get stuck into perceiving their class as defined through the set of existing skills instead of the original archetype.  IE "We have a lot of DOTs, so everything we do from here on out must be based solely upon improving this capacity."  I'm not denying that we need improvement in areas like this, but if we go that direction to the exclusion of enhancing the character of the "Necromancer" we are reduced to a flat uninspired avatar who is a "necromancer" only in name.  I guarantee you'll only find the class pretty boring.  Ask wizards how entertaining their class has become to play - one dimensional - yehah.  Same with clerics.  Granted, many spells we and other classes have are designed more to adhere to the game environment than to the ideal, but the ideal should always be the greater source for inspiration in furthering the class design.</P><P>That's my story and I'm stickin to it...</P><P></P><P></P><P>Edited by - Takilth SP on 06/13/2002  16:49:06</P><P>Edited by - Takilth SP on 06/13/2002  16:50:51<a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height="15" width="15" border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
